swore
to meet me on the plain;
With eager
haste
to that dear
spot
I flew,
And linger'd long, and then with tears withdrew:
Alone, abandon'd to love's
tenderest
woes,
Down my pale cheeks the tide of
sorrow
flows;
Dead to all joys that fortune can
bestow
,
In vain for me her
useless
bounties flow;
Take back each envied gift, ye pow'rs divine,
And only let me call
Fidelio
mine.
Ah, wretch! what
anguish
yet thy
